## Install

```bash
pipx install {{ name }}

# Or with uv
uv tool install {{ name }}
```

## Setup

Point it at your API instance:

```bash
export {{ env_prefix }}_BASE_URL=https://your-api-host
```

### Authentication

Depending on the spec's security scheme, set one of the following:

- **Bearer token** (e.g. JWT):
  ```bash
  export {{ env_prefix }}_TOKEN=your-token
  ```
- **API key header**:
  ```bash
  export {{ env_prefix }}_API_KEY=your-key
  ```
- **HTTP Basic auth**:
  ```bash
  export {{ env_prefix }}_USERNAME=your-username
  export {{ env_prefix }}_PASSWORD=your-password
  ```

The CLI auto-detects which scheme the spec declares and reads the matching env var.

## Usage

```bash
# List top-level command groups
{{ name }} --help

# Commands in a group
{{ name }} <group> --help

# Flags for a specific command
{{ name }} <group> <command> --help
```

## Output Formats

Every command accepts `--output-format`:

```bash
{{ name }} <group> <command> --output-format json    # default
{{ name }} <group> <command> --output-format table   # rich table
{{ name }} <group> <command> --output-format yaml
{{ name }} <group> <command> --output-format raw
```

## How It Works

This package is a thin wrapper:
- Embeds the OpenAPI spec (`spec.yaml`)
- Delegates CLI generation to [openapi-cli-gen](https://github.com/shivaam/openapi-cli-gen) at runtime

Since it's spec-driven, new endpoints show up automatically when the spec is regenerated — no manual wrapping to fall behind.

